Section 1: Context and description of the data¶

This dataset explores the chemical features and quality measurements of the vinho verde wine. The vinho verde wine is a unique product from the north-west region of Portugal that accounts for 15% of all Portuguese wine production. It is known to have medium amounts of alcohol and being particularly popular during the summer due to its fruity floral aroma. Though more commonly found as a white wine, the dataset contains both white and red variations.

The data was collected from May 2004 to February 2007 by the CVRVV, an organization dedicated to studying the vinho verde wine. Only samples assigned to the "protected designation of origin" (PDO) title were used. The PDO designation refers to a European Union specialization that is used to protect the quality of agricultural products. Thus, we can see that the samples used in this dataset consist of high quality wines, though they may not be representative of all vinho verde wines.

The chemical features of the samples were measured in a lab resulting in 11 variables including: acidity, sugar, chlorides, sulfur dioxide levels, density, pH, sulphates, and alcohol content. Quality of each wine was evaluated by taking the median of three blind taste test scores that ranged from 0 (very bad) to 10 (excellent). Though the data initially separated the white and red wines, we combined the two datasets in order to examine the differences between their chemical compositions. This resulted in a total of 6497 observations with 4898 white and 1599 red.

1.1 Basic Data Cleaning¶

In this section, we loaded the red and white wine datasets and combined the two together, so that we could later create the prediction model based on the color variable.

2.2 Quality¶

In this section, we were interested in examining whether the chemical compositions differed between quality score groups. We chose to group the quality scores into three divisions to prepare for our prediction model in which we would use a classification method to predict the quality of the wine: scores 3 and 4 were "low quality"; 5 and 6 were "medium quality"; and 6, 7, 8 were "high quality".
